      "type": "user-query",
      "text": "PLS SORT IT OUT FOR ME:\n\n}Understood! You want to bundle and deploy your Vue.js prototype directly inside\nyour custom Frappe app (fg_companion) so it is built, served, and managed\nnatively by the Frappe Bench, rather than running as a disconnected standalone\nproject.\n\nFrappe provides a standard way to embed single-page applications (SPAs) like\nyour portal directly inside a custom app.\n\nHere is how you structured your directory so that the Bench automatically\ncompiles your Vue.js project whenever you run bench build:\n\nStep 1: The Native Folder Structure\n\nInside your custom backend app directory (~/my-bench/apps/fg_companion), Frappe\nexpects a folder named frontend containing all of your Vue.js code:\n\n~/my-bench/apps/fg_companion/\n├── fg_companion/              # Backend Python code (DocTypes, API)\n└── frontend/                  # Your Vue.js / TypeScript project\n    ├── src/\n    ├── package.json           # Your Vite/Vue build configurations\n    ├── vite.config.ts         # Vite configuration\n    └── index.html\n\nTo move your prototype code into the app, you would copy the files from\nC:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\community-launchpad-proto into\n~/my-bench/apps/fg_companion/frontend/.\n\nStep 2: Configure Vite to Output to Frappe's Public Folder\n\nWhen you build a standard Vue app, it normally outputs static files to a dist/\nfolder. In a Frappe ecosystem, you want Vite to build the files directly into\nthe custom app's public directory so Frappe's web server can find and serve them\nnatively.\n\nModify your vite.config.ts inside frontend/ to point its output path directly to\nfg_companion's assets folder:\n\n// apps/fg_companion/frontend/vite.config.ts\nimport { defineConfig } from 'vite';\nimport vue from '@vitejs/plugin-vue';\nimport path from 'path';\n\nexport default defineConfig({\n  plugins: [vue()],\n  resolve: {\n    alias: {\n      '@': path.resolve(__dirname, './src'),\n    },\n  },\n  build: {\n    // This outputs the compiled production build directly into your custom app's public assets\n    outDir: '../fg_companion/public/frontend',\n    emptyOutDir: true,\n  },\n  server: {\n    // Proxy API calls during local development (yarn dev) straight to the bench\n    proxy: {\n      '/api': {\n        target: 'http://mysite.localhost:8000',\n        changeOrigin: true,\n      },\n    },\n  },\n});\n\nStep 3: Automate with package.json\n\nTo make sure bench build automatically triggers your Vue.js compilation\nalongside backend assets, add these scripts to the master package.json located\nin the root of your fg_companion app:\n\n// apps/fg_companion/package.json\n{\n  \"name\": \"fg_companion\",\n  \"scripts\": {\n    \"postinstall\": \"cd frontend && yarn install\",\n    \"build\": \"cd frontend && yarn build\"\n  }\n}\n\nNow, whenever you run bench build, your Vue.js code will compile directly into\nyour app assets!\n\nStep 4: Routing the Portal via www/\n\nTo serve the Vue app directly when someone visits\nhttp://mysite.localhost:8000/portal (or any custom route), create a template\npage inside your app's web folder:\n\n1.  Create a page at apps/fg_companion/fg_companion/www/portal.html:\n    <!-- Server-side jinja wrapper that injects your compiled SPA -->\n    <!DOCTYPE html>\n    <html lang=\"en\">\n    <head>\n        <meta charset=\"UTF-8\">\n        <title>Community Portal</title>\n        <!-- Load compiled esbuild/vite assets from the site -->\n        <link rel=\"stylesheet\" href=\"/assets/fg_companion/css/style.css\">\n    </head>\n    <body>\n        <div id=\"app\"></div>\n        <script type=\"module\" src=\"/assets/fg_companion/js/main.js\"></script>\n    </body>\n    </html>\n\nNow, your custom frontend, database, and backend apps are fully merged into one\ncohesive platform. When anyone navigates to your site, they will be greeted\ndirectly by your Vue.js layout, fueled by Frappe's high-speed backend!\n",
      "timestamp": 1781971369027
    },
    {
      "type": "answer",
      "text": "I'll help you integrate your Vue.js prototype into the Frappe ecosystem. Here's the complete setup:\n\n## Step 1: Move to Native Frappe App Structure\n\nNavigate to your bench and move your frontend code:\n\n```bash\n# Go to the fg_companion app\ncd ~/my-bench/apps/fg_companion\n\n# Backup and move your frontend code\nmkdir -p frontend\nmv -n ../frontend/* frontend/ 2>/dev/null || echo \"Some files may already exist\"\n\n# Copy your prototype files\ncp -r ~/community-launchpad-proto/* frontend/\n```\n\n## Step 2: Configure vite.config.ts\n\nEdit `~/my-bench/apps/fg_companion/frontend/vite.config.ts`:\n\n```typescript\nimport { defineConfig } from 'vite';\nimport vue from '@vitejs/plugin-vue';\nimport path from 'path';\n\nexport default defineConfig({\n  plugins: [vue()],\n  resolve: {\n    alias: {\n      '@': path.resolve(__dirname, './src'),\n    },\n  },\n  build: {\n    // Output directly to Frappe's public assets\n    outDir: '../fg_companion/public/frontend',\n    emptyOutDir: true,\n  },\n  server: {\n    // Proxy API calls during development to the bench\n    proxy: {\n      '/api': {\n        target: 'http://localhost:8000',\n        changeOrigin: true,\n      },\n    },\n  },\n});\n```\n\n## Step 3: Configure package.json\n\nEdit `~/my-bench/apps/fg_companion/package.json`:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"name\": \"fg_companion\",\n  \"scripts\": {\n    \"postinstall\": \"cd frontend && yarn install\",\n    \"build\": \"cd frontend && yarn build\",\n    \"dev\": \"cd frontend && yarn dev\"\n  },\n  \"dependencies\": {\n    // All your dependencies from community-launchpad-proto\n    \"vue\": \"^3.4.21\",\n    \"@vueuse/core\": \"^10.9.0\",\n    \"frappe-ui\": \"latest\",\n    // ... other dependencies\n  },\n  \"devDependencies\": {\n    // All your dev dependencies\n    \"@vitejs/plugin-vue\": \"^5.0.4\",\n    \"vite\": \"^8.0.16\",\n    // ... other dev dependencies\n  }\n}\n```\n\n## Step 4: Create the Web Page Template\n\nCreate `~/my-bench/apps/fg_companion/fg_companion/www/portal.html`:\n\n```html\n<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html lang=\"en\">\n<head>\n    <meta charset=\"UTF-8\">\n    <meta name=\"viewport\" content=\"width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0\">\n    <title>Community Portal</title>\n    <!-- Frappe will automatically link your compiled assets -->\n    <link rel=\"stylesheet\" href=\"/assets/fg_companion/css/frontend/style.css\">\n</head>\n<body>\n    <div id=\"app\"></div>\n    <!-- Frappe will automatically include your compiled JS -->\n    <script type=\"module\" src=\"/assets/fg_companion/js/frontend/main.js\"></script>\n</body>\n</html>\n```\n\n## Step 5: Configure the Route in Frappe\n\nAdd route mapping to `~/my-bench/apps/fg_companion/fg_companion/www.js`:\n\n```javascript\nfrappe.ready(function() {\n  frappe.route('/portal', function() {\n    frappe.render_template('portal', {});\n  });\n});\n```\n\n## Step 6: Install and Build\n\n```bash\n# Navigate to the app root\ncd ~/my-bench/apps/fg_companion\n\n# Install dependencies\nyarn install\n\n# Build everything\nbench build\n```\n\n## Step 7: Test Locally\n\n```bash\n# Start the bench\nbench start\n\n# Visit http://localhost:8000/portal\n```\n\n## Step 8: Update Your Vue App for Production\n\nUpdate `~/my-bench/apps/fg_companion/frontend/src/main.ts` to handle Frappe context:\n\n```typescript\nimport { createApp } from 'vue'\nimport App from './App.vue'\nimport router from './router'\n\n// Wait for Frappe to be ready\ndocument.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {\n  const app = createApp(App)\n  app.use(router)\n  app.mount('#app')\n})\n```\n\n## Key Benefits:\n\n1. **Automatic Integration**: `bench build` now compiles your Vue app directly into Frappe assets\n2. **Native Hosting**: Your portal is served as a native Frappe page\n3. **Database Integration**: Full access to Frappe's ORM, authentication, and user management\n4. **Real Backend**: Your Vue app can access all Frappe apps via API calls\n5. **Performance**: Assets are cached and served by Frappe's web server\n\n## Final Structure:\n\n```\n~/my-bench/apps/fg_companion/\n├── fg_companion/              # Backend Python code\n├── frontend/                  # Your Vue.js code\n│   ├── src/\n│   ├── package.json\n│   └── vite.config.ts\n└── fg_companion/\n    ├── www/portal.html       # Page template\n    ├── www.js                 # Route configuration\n    └── public/                # Frappe will create this\n        └── frontend/          # Your compiled assets\n```\n\nNow your Vue.js prototype is fully integrated into the Frappe ecosystem! The bench will automatically compile and serve it alongside all your backend functionality.",
